author: @muhammadabdullahdilshad8509
text: Notes : num= 3 # type tells us the data type  print(type(num)) num2 = 3.4 print(type(num2))  # Arithemtatics print(3+2) print(3-2) print(3*2) print(3/2) #Gives us the exact Value (1.5) print(3//2) #Gives us the floor value (1) print(3**2) # 3 raised to power 2 print(3 % 2) #Modulus   #Order of Precedence print(3*(2+1)) #Parenthesis First  # Increment num3 = 1 num3 +=3 print(num3)  # Abs built In function num4 = -5 print(abs(num4))  # Round FUnction print(round(3.75,1)) #round of two first Number  # Comaprisons #comparisons return Booleans num_1 = 3 num_2 = 2  print(num_1 == num_2) print(num_1 != num_2) print(num_1 > num_2) print(num_1 < num_2) print(num_1 <= num_2) print(num_1 >= num_2)   #suppose Numbers are in the form of strings num_1 = "100" num_2 = "200" #to Convert these strings into Integeres we use Casting num_1 = int(num_1) num_2 = int(num_2) print(num_1 + num_2)

author: @immortalized_onion
text: Some notes:  ------- Numbers -------  Types :- - int, normal integers like, -2,3,0 etc - float, decimal/fractional values like, -0.4, 9.83 etc.  Arithmetic Operators :-  - 3 + 2  # Addition        - 3 - 2  # Subtraction     - 3 * 2  # Multiplication  - 3 / 2  # Division        - 3 // 2  # Floor Division (rounds float to int) - 3 ** 2  # Exponent        - 3 % 2 # Modulus (remainder)   Comparisons :-      - return either true or false   - 3 == 2  # Equal - 3 != 2 # Not Equal       - 3 > 2 # Greater Than    - 3 < 2 # Less Than       - 3 >= 2 # Greater or Equal - 3 <= 2 # Less or Equal    Incrementing :- num = 1 num += 1  # same as num = num + 1 # the "+" in += can be replaced by any other arthimetic Operators # eg num *= 2, now num = num * 2 = 2. Similarly all other arthimetics.  Useful functions :- 1. Absolute value function - abs(value)  - gives the magnitude of integers.  - basically, removes the negative sign if there is one. - abs(-3) # returns 3 2. round function - round(value) . - Also accepts another argument to specify no. of digits  - after the decimal point to round the value off to. - round(3.75) # returns 4 - round(3.75, 1) # returns 3.8, ie. 1 digit  Type conversion/casting :- - int(value) - num = "1"   int(num) # returns 1 as an integer  Miscellaneous :- - Add parentheses () for enforcing precedence. eg: 3 * (2+1) = 9 - you can use type(variable_or_value) to find the value's data type.

text: Hi. I'm a super newb and came across the following in an exercise. We haven't discussed how to do what this guy did in the walk-through video, so I'm a bit confused. The guy in the video mentioned the thing I'm having an issue with as being a 'float', which is how I ended up on your video here.    The entire project is below, but the part that jacked me up was the: print(     "The cheapest option available is $%.2f with %s"       % (cost, method))    I'm not sure what the % signs, the .2f and the s are doing in this string.   Any help would be greatly appreciated.  ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- def print_cheapest_method(weight):    ground = shipping_cost_ground(weight)     premium = shipping_cost_premium    drone = shipping_cost_drone(weight)    if ground < premium and ground < drone:     method = "standard ground shipping"     cost = ground   elif premium < ground and premium < drone:     method = "premium ground shipping"     cost = premium   else:      method = "drone shipping"     cost = drone    print(     "The cheapest option available is $%.2f with %s"       % (cost, method))    # Now, test your function!  # What is the cheapest method of shipping a 4.8 pound package and how much would it cost?  # What is the cheapest method of shipping a 41.5 pound package and how much would it cost?  print_cheapest_method(4.8) print_cheapest_method(41.5)

author: @mohamedghazali4914
text: #Arithmetic operators  # Addition:       3 + 2 # Subtraction:    3 - 3 # Multiplication: 3 * 2 # Division:       3 / 2 # Floor Division: 3 // 2 # Exponent:       3 ** 2 # Modulus:        3 % 2   num1= 25 num2=3.14 print(type(num1)) print(type(num2))  #incrementing Values num = 7 num = num + 1 #or you can say # num +=1 print(num)  #Absolute Value print(abs(-3))  #Round print('the round of 3.75 is:')  print(round(3.75)) print(round(3.75, 1))   #Comparison operators   # Equal:             3 == 2  # Not Equal:         3 != 2  # Greater Than:      3 > 2  # less Than:         3< 2  # Greater  or Equal: 3 >= 2  # Less  or Equal:    3 <= 2   num_1 = 3 num_2 = 2 print('Comparison operators') print(num_1 == num_2) print(num_1 != num_2) print(num_1 > num_2) print(num_1 < num_2) print(num_1 >= num_2) print(num_1 <= num_2)  #Casting  number_1 = '100' number_2 = '200'  number_1 = int(number_1) number_2 = int(number_2)  print(number_1 + number_2) #or you can write print(int(number_1 + number_2))
